<h2>Indian-specific FAQs</h2>

<div class="faq-item">
  <h3>Is ChatGPT free in India?</h3>
  <p>Yes. The free tier works in India without any restrictions. You just need a phone number to sign up — Indian numbers are accepted.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
  <h3>Why does my Indian debit card get rejected on ChatGPT?</h3>
  <p>Most Indian debit cards block international transactions by default. You need to either enable international transactions in your bank app, or use a forex card like Niyo Global, HDFC Forex Plus, or IDFC FIRST Forex.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
  <h3>Can I share my ChatGPT Plus account with family in India?</h3>
  <p>Officially no — OpenAI's terms allow only personal use. Practically, many Indian families do share accounts and don't get caught. Use at your own risk; sharing widely (4+ devices) does trigger flags.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
  <h3>Does ChatGPT understand Hindi well?</h3>
  <p>Yes, Hindi performance is now production-grade. You can have full conversations in Hindi, Hinglish, or mixed languages. Output quality is comparable to English for most tasks.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
  <h3>Is ChatGPT safe for Indian businesses to use with confidential data?</h3>
  <p>By default, OpenAI may train on your free-tier chats. For business use, either turn off chat history (privacy mode) or use the Team/Enterprise tier where data isn't used for training. For genuinely sensitive data, Claude's default policies are stricter.</p>
</div>

<h2>Final verdict</h2>

<p>ChatGPT is the safest "first AI tool" for an Indian user — widely supported, well-documented, large community for help. The image generation and voice mode are genuinely useful and not easily replicated by competitors.</p>

<p>But if your primary use is text-heavy work (writing, research, coding, legal/business documents), Claude probably gives you more for the same money. Compare them side by side: <a href="/vs/chatgpt-vs-claude-india/">ChatGPT vs Claude for Indians</a>.</p>

